post_text:
The month of August focuses on Altruism: the unselfish concern for other people‚Äîdoing things simply out of a desire to help, not because you feel obligated to out of duty, loyalty, or religious reasons. I hope that you can make some use of these small daily actions to increase your own happiness and the well-being of others.

"Altruism is vital for the human race to survive and thrive; and each of our lives is supported by countless kind acts from other people. Yet in our world today, so much is directing us to think only about ourselves - and we often forget the happiness that comes by caring for others. We want to change that. This August Action for Happiness asking everyone to take one kind act per day. Let's create a wave of kindness to spread around the world." ~ Action for Happiness Keep Calm ~ Stay Wise ~ Be Kind

post_text:
A message from Superintendent Schutz

-Brooks Families: Yesterday, TEA released guidelines regarding a safe return to on-campus instruction for the new school year. You can read this information at https://tea.texas.gov/coronavirus. Unfortunately, this guidance didn't provide all the specifics we were looking for, but please know that nothing is more important than the safety of our staff and students and we will adhere to all guidelines and put other safety measures in place as well. We continue to prepare for implementation of our VIP (Virtual and IP-Person) Plan - by August 10, we will ask you to make a decision about how your child(ren) will attend the first six-week grading period. Please feel free to contact your school leaders if you have any questions and we'll do our best to answer them. We will continue to update you as we get information, or if the guidelines change.

Unfortunately, this guidance didn't provide all the specifics we were looking for, but please know that nothing is more important than the safety of our staff and students and we will adhere to all guidelines and put other safety measures in place as well. We continue to prepare for implementation of our VIP (Virtual and IP-Person) Plan - by August 10, we will ask you to make a decision about how your child(ren) will attend the first six-week grading period. Please feel free to contact your school leaders if you have any questions and we'll do our best to answer them. We will continue to update you as we get information, or if the guidelines change.

text: Friendly Reminder.....

post_text:
The month of July focuses on Resilience; I hope that you can make some use of these small daily actions to increase your own happiness and overall well-being.

"All of us have times of stress, loss, failure or trauma in our lives. But how we respond to these has a big impact on our wellbeing.We often cannot choose what happens to us, but in principle we can choose our own attitude to what happens. In practice it's not always easy, but one of the most exciting findings from recent research is that resilience, like many other life skills, can be learned."

Hope you all continue to have a great summer!

Keep Calm ~ Stay Wise ~ Be Kind

Explore cryptography, secret codes, and ciphers! Students are introduced to the substitution cipher, which hides messages by replacing letters or groups of letters with other letters or groups of letters. post_text:
Brooks Academy hosted a Zoom meeting between Students from Principle of Business, Economics and AP Spanish and representatives of Consulate General of Mexico in San Antonio.
The visitors were:
Efr√©n Pati√±o - Economic Affair Department
Consuls Lluvia Ponce and Alexia Bautista
Dr. Rub√©n Minutti - Consul General of Mexico
Our guest speakers were able to tell us some history of Mexico, including later events that contribute to Economical relationship between US, Mexico and Canada. They shared information about the international trade and consular diplomacy. Students were able to ask questions about opportunities that will be available to them in the future.
At the end of the class our guest Congratulated our Seniors and wish them luck.

post_text:
Special message from Parent of 2nd Grader Jonathan.
Mrs. Tara Doebbler. My son Jonathan Fernandez has had her as his teacher in Kinder and now in 2nd grade. I can not put into words the positive impact this teacher has made on my child. Her kindness, patience, understanding and compassion as a teacher towards ALL her students is beyond exemplary. Showing appreciation for Mrs. Doebbler just for a week is not merely enough. I have had the pleasure as a parent to see her interact with her students and the attention to detail she applies to their education only exemplifies her BIG Heart and her genuine caring nature. She treats every student as a "Shinning STAR" and in my opinion emphasizes to each student, that ANY dream can become a reality!
We as a family believe teachers are Angels in disguise!!!
Thank you Mrs. Doebbler, for being a one of a kind Teacher at BASE....

Families, we will continue to have curbside service for meals at each campus from 7 a.m. to 1 p.m. for the remainder of this week. Beginning Monday, March 30, we will distribute meal kits with five breakfasts and five lunches per student. This service will take place at all four campuses. Please complete this survey to let us know whether you will be using the Monday curbside pick-up for your students‚Äô weekly meals. Curbside pick-up will be each Monday from 7 a.m. to 10 a.m. Questions? Please email Christine.VanHoozer@brooksacademy.org

These meals are FREE regardless of previous eligibility.

post_text:
Families, this is what we know about STAAR: It has been cancelled for this year.

TEA will provide guidance on waivers and grad plans for seniors who may still need one or more EOCS so that they will graduate.

STAAR-ALT-2 is cancelled for this year.

TEA is working with the federal government to determine how TELPAS and LPACs will be handled.

TEA is working with college board to determine how AP testing will be handled.

TEA is working on a plan to determine how EOCs will be handled (if they will be waived or if they will be taken in August).

We will continue updating you.

The LEAP class did an exercise to pay homage to the late great Kobe Bryant in honor of Black History Month. The class was split into 2 teams ‚Äú8‚Äù and ‚Äú24.‚Äù
Each student was asked to draw pictures of things that they fear. When they were done they were asked to crumble up their ‚Äúfears‚Äù into a ball. Students then stood behind a line and shot their fears into the trash. The shot only counted if they yelled ‚ÄúKobe!‚Äù Moral of the lesson was that fear kills more dreams than anything else. Face them, conquer them and don‚Äôt let them hold you back! Live life and challenge yourself by doing something that scares you. @ Brooks Academy of Science and Engineering - Official Pg

post_text:
For the second year in a row we are participating in the BexarFest Multimedia Festival. This year we teamed up with the San Antonio Mastersingers!

BexarFest pairs high school media production teams from Atascosa, Bandera, Bexar, Comal, Guadalupe, Kendall, Medina and Wilson counties with local nonprofit organizations to create outreach media for the nonprofit to use in its marketing campaigns.

The purpose of BexarFest is to give high school students experience in media production and an in-depth look at how nonprofit organizations operate. Working as a team, students practice communications, resource allocation, time management and other workplace skills. At the same time, nonprofits participating in BexarFest give students the opportunity to experience community service while receiving free tools to use in their outreach campaigns.

The viewing and award show at the Tobin Center is this upcoming Wednesday, Feb. 19, 2020.

Rose Scotello took Best Female Newcomer and Phoenix Talamantez took Female MVP of the District! All are advancing and will compete next week at Regional Championships in Austin. @ Brooks Academy of Science and Engineering - Official Pg

post_text:
Hello and happy holidays to all of our BASE families! We know that while the holiday season is full of joy, it can also be a difficult time for some families who are experiencing financial hardships. This year we will be hosting our third annual Angel Tree drive for our students whose families cannot financially manage holiday gifts at this time. If you and your family are in need this year, please email Robert.Alexander@brooksacademy.org or Kelli.Fitzpatrick@brooksacademy.org with a gift suggestion for each child in your family. Please turn in your gift requests no later than December 2.



The anonymous gift requests will be placed in the form of ornaments on a tree at our school and volunteers will help fulfill those wishes. If you would like to help fulfill an anonymous wish, more details will be provided soon."



#basegivesback

shared_text:
Brooks Academies
May 21, 2019 at 3:21 PM ¬∑

Today, Juniors from BASE Brooks Academy of Science and Engineering - Official Pg were invited to participate in a regional summit hosted by UTSA‚Äôs Institute of Texan Cultures in conjunction with the Smithsonian National Youth Summit: Woman Suffrage the Ballot and Beyond. Students heard from Naomi Wadler, Paige Harrington and famed activist Dolores Huerta from Washington DC. Students then had the opportunity to meet and hear from local activists and community leaders Rosie Castro, Pat Jasso, Councilwoman Rebecca Viagran, and Dr. Yvonne Katz. Presenters inspired our students to always fight for what they believe in!
